A solution here is to use [`Pool.apply` or `Pool.apply_async`](https://docs.python.org/2/library/multiprocessing.html#module-multiprocessing.pool):

    greetings = list(
        multiprocessing.Pool(2).apply(greet, kwds={&#39;greetee&#39;: greetees[i]})
        for i in range(len(greetees))
    )
    for greeting in greetings:
        print(greeting)

Output:

    Hello, Foo!
    Hello, Bar!

Courtesy of [Mad Physicist](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58453691/how-to-apply-keyword-only-arguments-to-a-function-in-a-multiprocessing-pool/58454015#comment103245107_58453692) and [this QnA](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/35761325/using-the-multiprocessing-pool-map-function-with-keyword-arguments), one can use [functools.partial](https://docs.python.org/3.7/library/functools.html#functools.partial) to inject keyword-only arguments into a function:

    from functools import partial
    greetings = []
    for i in range(len(greetees)):
        kwargs = {&#39;greetee&#39;: greetees[i]}
        greet_partial = partial(greet, **kwargs)
        greetings.append(multiprocessing.Pool(2).apply(greet_partial))

Or with less variable bleed:

    from functools import partial
    greetings = [
        multiprocessing.Pool(2).apply(
            partial(greet, **{&#39;greetee&#39;: greetees[i]})
        )
        for i in range(len(greetees))
    ]

